Mexico and Central America
---
Mexico (national). 21 Mar 2016. (registered) 160 cases, of whom 30 are pregnant women. States most affected: Chiapas 82 cases, Oaxaca 59 cases, Guerrero 7 cases, Nuevo León 4 cases, Jalisco 2 cases, Michoacán, Nayarit, Sinaloa, Tabasco, Veracruz, Yucatán 1 case each.
http://www.e-consulta.com/nota/2016-03-21/nacion/avanza-160-el-numero-de-casos-de-infectados-con-el-virus-del-zika [in Spanish]

Panama (national). 21 Mar 2016. (confirmed (conf)) 149 cases. Localities affected: provinces of Panamá, Colón, Panamá Oeste, comarca de Guna Yala.
http://www.tvn-2.com/nacionales/salud/Aumentan-casos-virus-zika_0_4442555719.html

Caribbean
---
US Virgin Islands
- St Croix. 19 Mar 2016. (conf) 11 cases.
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/us-virgin-islands-more-zika-confirmed-in-st-croix-14291/

- St Thomas. 21 Mar 2016. (conf) 1st case on the island. Samples taken 1 month ago.
http://stthomassource.com/content/news/local-news/2016/03/21/st-thomas-reports-first-case-zika

Trinidad (national). 22 Mar 2016. (conf) 6 cases, at least 3 locally acquired.
https://www.guardian.co.tt/news/2016-03-22/gulf-view-man-sixth-zika-case

Martinique (national). 2 Mar 2016. (reported) 1st case of microcephaly (suspected (susp)) linked to Zika virus infection of mother.
http://news.statetimes.in/suspected-zika-linked-birth-defect-french-island/

South America
---
Argentina (Corrientes province). 22 Mar 2016. (conf) 2 cases imported [locality where the infections were acquired not stated].
http://www.telam.com.ar/notas/201603/140483-dengue-zika-corrientes.html [in Spanish]

Brazil
- Microcephaly cases. 22 Mar 2016. (susp) as of 19 Mar 2016, 4293 cases, (conf) 907 cases. [The relationship of these cases to Zika virus infection of the mother not stated.]
http://kdal610.com/news/articles/2016/mar/22/brazil-says-confirmed-and-suspected-microcephaly-cases-rise-to-5200/

- Virus arrival. 24 Mar 2016. (reported) Zika likely arrive in Brazil between May - December 2013, probably from French Polynesia or SE Asia. The full genome of virus samples taken from 7 Brazilian patients who were infected with Zika between March and November 2015 were determined. Genomes of the Brazilian samples were compared to those from patients in 9 other countries, 6 from the current outbreak in the Americas and one each from French Polynesia, the Cook Islands, and Thailand. The sequences from the Americas were the most closely related; the sequence from a patient in Thailand in 2013 was the most distant. That's consistent with the leading theory that the virus entered Brazil only once, from someone infected in the 2013 Zika epidemic in French Polynesia, and spread to the rest of the Americas from there.
http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2016/03/don-t-blame-sports-zika-s-spread

Chile (national). 24 Mar 2016. (conf.) the 1st autochthonous case of Zika virus infection in Continental Chilean territory has been documented by the Virology Laboratory of the School of Medicine, Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile.

Early this year (2016) the male partner traveled to a country with active Zika virus transmission. He presented with Zika symptoms and the infection was confirmed retrospectively by serology (Zika IgM positive and IgG seroconversion in a convalescent sample). Dengue IgM was negative. While he was symptomatic he had sexual intercourse with his female partner. She presented with rash, retroauricular adenopathies, conjunctivitis, and arthritis, and was diagnosed of Zika infection by Zika positive IgM and Zika IgG seroconversion in a convalescent blood sample. She also traveled to the same affected country as her male partner and to 2 other countries, one with Zika virus transmission, another without (but spent a few hours in the airport only). Her disease started 18 and 14 days respectively after possible exposure in countries with Zika [virus] transmission. Considering a Zika [virus infection] incubation period of up to 12 days, vector transmission is very unlikely.

This is the 1st documented case of Zika infection by sexual transmission in Chile, being also the 1st case acquired in continental Chilean territory, where there is no presence of _Aedes_ [vector] mosquitoes.

[ProMED-mail thanks Cecilia Perret MD <cperret@med.puc.cl> and Marcela Ferrés MD of the School of Medicine, Virology Laboratory, Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, for sending in this case report. - Mod.TY]

Asia
---
China (national). 9 Mar 2016. (reported) 1 Zika virus isolate from 1 imported case of the 10 cases in China was sequenced. It is related to the Asia genotype.
(Deng YQ, Zhao H, Li XF, et al. Isolation, identification and genomic characterization of the Asian lineage Zika virus imported to China. Sci China Life Sci. 2016; doi: 10.1007/s11427-016-5043-4; http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11427-016-5043-4)

