- North Queensland state. 21 Mar 2016. (reported) 13 cases: the latest case (conf) is imported from Tonga [the locality of acquisition of virus infection of the 12 other cases not stated].
http://www.ibtimes.com.au/zika-queensland-woman-tests-positive-bowen-residents-asked-use-mosquito-repellents-aggressively

[An imported suspected case, probably from the Caribbean, was reported in Cairns, in far north Queensland on 23 Mar 2016. Cairns and other parts of the state's far north have previously been identified as problem areas for Zika because they are the areas of Australia most likely to see an outbreak due to the presence of _Aedes aegypti_. (http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/suspected-zika-virus-case-in-cairns-triggers-more-mosquito-spraying-20160323-gnppcd.html).

